only thing that changes between isotopologues is \(\mu\). This leads to a useful insight: substituting a heavier isotope on the light atom has a much larger effect than substituting on the heavy atom. For example, in HBr: Replacing \({}^{79}\ce{Br}\) with \({}^{81}\ce{Br}\) changes \(\mu\) by about 0.03%. The rotational spectrum is almost unaffected, and using the average atomic mass for bromine is a perfectly good approximation. Replacing \({}^{1}\ce{H}\) with \({}^{2}\ce{H}\) (deuterium) nearly doubles \(\mu\) (from about 0.99 to 1.95 amu). This produces a dramatically different rotational spectrum. Isotope substitution on the light atom has the largest effect on the reduced mass (and therefore on \(B\)), because a small absolute change in mass represents a large fractional change. Going from \({}^{1}\ce{H}\) to \({}^{2}\ce{H}\) is a 100% increase in mass; going from \({}^{79}\ce{Br}\) to \({}^{81}\ce{Br}\) is only 2.5%.
